{
 "cells": [
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "# Comparative Analysis of Numerical Methods for Black-Scholes PDE"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "This notebook performs a comprehensive comparative analysis of the implemented numerical methods (Analytical Black-Scholes, Binomial Tree, Monte Carlo, and Finite Difference) for option pricing. It loads data from the SQLite database, compares the results based on accuracy, computational efficiency, and provides visualizations of key findings."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "import pandas as pd\n",
    "import matplotlib.pyplot as plt\n",
    "import seaborn as sns\n",
    "import sqlite3\n",
    "import os\n",
    "import sys\n",
    "import numpy as np\n",
    "\n",
    "# Add the project root to sys.path for importing modules\n",
    "sys.path.insert(0, os.path.abspath(os.path.join(os.getcwd(), '..', '..')))\n",
    "\n",
    "from src.data import database\n",
    "from src.options.base import Option\n",
    "from src.analytical.black_scholes import BlackScholes\n",
    "\n",
    "# --- Configuration ---"",
    "DATABASE_PATH = os.path.abspath(os.path.join(os.getcwd(), '..', '..', 'option_pricing_data.db'))\n",
    "print(f\"Database path: {DATABASE_PATH}\")\n",
    "\n",
    "# --- Load Data ---"",
    "conn = database.connect_db(DATABASE_PATH)\n",
    "\n",
    "options_df = pd.read_sql_query(\"SELECT * FROM options\", conn)\n",
    "results_df = pd.read_sql_query(\"SELECT * FROM results\", conn)\n",
    "market_data_df = pd.read_sql_query(\"SELECT * FROM market_data\", conn)\n",
    "\n",
    "conn.close()\n",
    "\n",
    "print(\"Data loaded successfully:\")\n",
    "print(f\"Options: {len(options_df)} records\")\n",
    "print(f\"Results: {len(results_df)} records\")\n",
    "print(f\"Market Data: {len(market_data_df)} records\")\n",
    "\n",
    "# Merge options and results for easier analysis\n",
    "merged_df = pd.merge(results_df, options_df, left_on='option_id', right_on='id', suffixes=('_result', '_option'))\n",
    "merged_df.rename(columns={'id_option': 'option_params_id'}, inplace=True)\n",
    "\n",
    "print(\"\\nMerged DataFrame head:\")\n",
    "merged_df.head()\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## 1. Price Comparison: Analytical vs. Numerical Methods"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "This section compares the option prices calculated by different methods for a selected option. We expect numerical methods to approximate the analytical Black-Scholes price for European options."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# Filter for a specific option (e.g., the first call option in the database)"",
    "example_option_id = options_df[options_df['option_type'] == 'call'].iloc[0]['id']\n",
    "example_option_data = merged_df[merged_df['option_id'] == example_option_id].copy()\n",
    "\n",
    "plt.figure(figsize=(12, 7))\n",
    "sns.barplot(x='method', y='price', data=example_option_data)\n",
    "plt.title(f'Price Comparison for Option ID {example_option_id} (S={example_option_data[\"S\"].iloc[0]}, K={example_option_data[\"K\"].iloc[0]}, T={example_option_data[\"T\"].iloc[0]}, r={example_option_data[\"r\"].iloc[0]}, sigma={example_option_data[\"sigma\"].iloc[0]})')\n",
    "plt.ylabel('Option Price')\n",
    "plt.xlabel('Pricing Method')\n",
    "plt.xticks(rotation=45, ha='right')\n",
    "plt.grid(axis='y', linestyle='--')\n",
    "plt.tight_layout()\n",
    "plt.show()\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## 2. Error Analysis (vs. Analytical Black-Scholes)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "We analyze the absolute and relative errors of numerical methods compared to the Black-Scholes analytical solution. This helps in understanding the accuracy of each method."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# Get analytical price for comparison"",
    "analytical_price_row = example_option_data[example_option_data['method'] == 'BlackScholes']\n",
    "if not analytical_price_row.empty:\n",
    "    analytical_price = analytical_price_row['price'].iloc[0]\n",
    "    \n",
    "    # Calculate absolute and relative error"",
    "    example_option_data['absolute_error'] = abs(example_option_data['price'] - analytical_price)\n",
    "    example_option_data['relative_error'] = abs((example_option_data['price'] - analytical_price) / analytical_price)\n",
    "    \n",
    "    # Filter out Black-Scholes itself for error plots"",
    "    numerical_methods_errors = example_option_data[example_option_data['method'] != 'BlackScholes']\n",
    "\n",
    "    plt.figure(figsize=(14, 6))\n",
    "    \n",
    "    plt.subplot(1, 2, 1)\n",
    "    sns.barplot(x='method', y='absolute_error', data=numerical_methods_errors)\n",
    "    plt.title(f'Absolute Error vs. Black-Scholes (Option ID {example_option_id})')\n",
    "    plt.ylabel('Absolute Error')\n",
    "    plt.xlabel('Numerical Method')\n",
    "    plt.xticks(rotation=45, ha='right')\n",
    "    plt.grid(axis='y', linestyle='--')\n",
    "\n",
    "    plt.subplot(1, 2, 2)\n",
    "    sns.barplot(x='method', y='relative_error', data=numerical_methods_errors)\n",
    "    plt.title(f'Relative Error vs. Black-Scholes (Option ID {example_option_id})')\n",
    "    plt.ylabel('Relative Error')\n",
    "    plt.xlabel('Numerical Method')\n",
    "    plt.xticks(rotation=45, ha='right')\n",
    "    plt.grid(axis='y', linestyle='--')\n",
    "    plt.tight_layout()\n",
    "    plt.show()\n",
    "else:\n",
    "    print(\"Analytical Black-Scholes price not found for error analysis.\")"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## 3. Computational Time Comparison"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "This section compares the computational time taken by each pricing method. Efficiency is a critical factor, especially for real-time applications or large-scale simulations."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "plt.figure(figsize=(12, 7))\n",
    "sns.barplot(x='method', y='computation_time', data=example_option_data)\n",
    "plt.title(f'Computational Time Comparison for Option ID {example_option_id}')\n",
    "plt.ylabel('Time (seconds)')\n",
    "plt.xlabel('Pricing Method')\n",
    "plt.xticks(rotation=45, ha='right')\n",
    "plt.grid(axis='y', linestyle='--')\n",
    "plt.yscale('log') # Use log scale for better visualization if times vary widely\n",
    "plt.tight_layout()\n",
    "plt.show()\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## 4. Greeks Comparison"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Greeks (Delta, Gamma, Vega, Theta, Rho) measure the sensitivity of the option price to changes in underlying parameters. We compare the analytical Greeks with those from numerical methods (where available or easily derivable)."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "greeks_columns = ['delta', 'gamma', 'vega', 'theta', 'rho']\n",
    "greeks_data = example_option_data[['method'] + greeks_columns].set_index('method')\n",
    "\n",
    "fig, axes = plt.subplots(nrows=len(greeks_columns), ncols=1, figsize=(12, 5 * len(greeks_columns)))\n",
    "fig.suptitle(f'Greeks Comparison for Option ID {example_option_id}', y=1.02, fontsize=16)\n",
    "\n",
    "for i, greek in enumerate(greeks_columns):\n",
    "    sns.barplot(x=greeks_data.index, y=greeks_data[greek], ax=axes[i])\n",
    "    axes[i].set_title(f'{greek.capitalize()}')\n",
    "    axes[i].set_ylabel(greek.capitalize())\n",
    "    axes[i].set_xlabel('')\n",
    "    axes[i].tick_params(axis='x', rotation=45, ha='right')\n",
    "    axes[i].grid(axis='y', linestyle='--')\n",
    "\n",
    "plt.tight_layout()\n",
    "plt.show()\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## 5. Market Data Validation: Model Prices vs. Market Prices"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "This section compares the model-generated prices with actual market prices fetched from `yfinance`. We use the mid-price (average of bid and ask) as a proxy for the market price."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# Select a market option to compare with"",
    "if not market_data_df.empty:\n",
    "    # For simplicity, let's pick one market option that matches our test_option parameters as closely as possible"",
    "    # In a real scenario, you'd match by S, K, T, option_type, and trade_date"",
    "    \n",
    "    # Find the analytical price for the test option"",
    "    analytical_price_for_test_option = merged_df[(merged_df['option_id'] == example_option_id) & \n",
    "                                                 (merged_df['method'] == 'BlackScholes')]['price'].iloc[0]\n",
    "\n",
    "    # Find a corresponding market option"",
    "    # This is a simplified match; a robust comparison would involve more sophisticated matching logic"",
    "    matched_market_option = market_data_df[\n",
    "        (market_data_df['strike_price'] == example_option_data['K'].iloc[0]) &\n",
    "        (market_data_df['option_type'] == example_option_data['option_type'].iloc[0])\n",
    "    ].sort_values(by='expiration_date').iloc[0] # Take the earliest expiring match\n",
    "\n",
    "    market_mid_price = (matched_market_option['bid_price'] + matched_market_option['ask_price']) / 2\n",
    "    market_implied_vol = matched_market_option['implied_volatility']\n",
    "\n",
    "    print(f\"Analytical Black-Scholes Price: {analytical_price_for_test_option:.4f}\")\n",
    "    print(f\"Market Mid-Price (matched option): {market_mid_price:.4f}\")\n",
    "    print(f\"Difference (Model - Market): {analytical_price_for_test_option - market_mid_price:.4f}\")\n",
    "    print(f\"Market Implied Volatility: {market_implied_vol:.4f}\")\n",
    "\n",
    "    # Plotting comparison"",
    "    comparison_prices = pd.DataFrame({\n",
    "        'Source': ['Analytical Black-Scholes', 'Market Mid-Price'],\n",
    "        'Price': [analytical_price_for_test_option, market_mid_price]\n",
    "    })\n",
    "\n",
    "    plt.figure(figsize=(8, 5))\n",
    "    sns.barplot(x='Source', y='Price', data=comparison_prices)\n",
    "    plt.title('Model Price vs. Market Price')\n",
    "    plt.ylabel('Price')\n",
    "    plt.grid(axis='y', linestyle='--')\n",
    "    plt.tight_layout()\n",
    "    plt.show()\n",
    "\n",
    "else:\n",
    "    print(\"No market data available for validation.\")"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## 6. Implied Volatility Smile/Skew from Market Data"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "The Black-Scholes model assumes constant volatility, but real markets exhibit a 'volatility smile' or 'skew'. This plot visualizes the implied volatility across different strike prices for a given expiration from market data."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "if not market_data_df.empty:\n",
    "    # Filter for a specific ticker and expiration for clarity"",
    "    spy_market_data = market_data_df[market_data_df['ticker'] == 'SPY']\n",
    "    if not spy_market_data.empty:\n",
    "        latest_expiration = spy_market_data['expiration_date'].max()\n",
    "        spy_market_data_latest_exp = spy_market_data[spy_market_data['expiration_date'] == latest_expiration].copy()\n",
    "        \n",
    "        # Clean up implied volatility data (remove inf/-inf or NaN)"",
    "        spy_market_data_latest_exp = spy_market_data_latest_exp[np.isfinite(spy_market_data_latest_exp['implied_volatility'])]\n",
    "\n",
    "        if not spy_market_data_latest_exp.empty:\n",
    "            plt.figure(figsize=(12, 7))\n",
    "            sns.scatterplot(x='strike_price', y='implied_volatility', hue='option_type', data=spy_market_data_latest_exp)\n",
    "            plt.title(f'Implied Volatility Smile/Skew for SPY (Exp: {latest_expiration})')\n",
    "            plt.xlabel('Strike Price')\n",
    "            plt.ylabel('Implied Volatility')\n",
    "            plt.grid(True, linestyle='--')\n",
    "            plt.tight_layout()\n",
    "            plt.show()\n",
    "        else:\n",
    "            print(\"No valid implied volatility data for SPY for the latest expiration.\")\n",
    "    else:\n",
    "        print(\"No SPY market data found for implied volatility analysis.\")\n",
    "else:\n",
    "    print(\"No market data found for implied volatility analysis.\")"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## 7. Conclusion and Further Work"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "This analysis provides a foundational comparison of various option pricing models. Key observations include:\n",
    "- **Accuracy:** Black-Scholes provides a benchmark for European options. Numerical methods approximate this, with varying degrees of accuracy depending on parameters and method choice.\n",
    "- **Computational Efficiency:** Different methods exhibit distinct performance characteristics, which are crucial for practical applications.\n",
    "- **Market Discrepancies:** Real market prices and implied volatilities often deviate from simple Black-Scholes assumptions, highlighting the need for more advanced models or adjustments.\n",
    "\n",
    "**Further Work could include:**\n",
    "- **Convergence Studies:** Systematically varying `n_steps`/`n_paths` to observe convergence rates.\n",
    "- **American Option Analysis:** Comparing American option pricing from Binomial Trees with other benchmarks.\n",
    "- **Advanced Models:** Implementing models that account for volatility smile/skew (e.g., local volatility, stochastic volatility models).\n",
    "- **Real-time Data Integration:** Connecting to live data feeds for continuous validation.\n",
    "- **NSE Data Integration:** Expanding data collection to include the Nairobi Securities Exchange for emerging market analysis."
   ]
  }
 ],
